items.title: Gonocarpus humilis
items.content_text: One straggly plant on a dry creek. New species record for Conglomerate Gully and Riddells Creek.

items.title: Senecio microbasis
items.content_text: Last flowers of the season for this species. ID confirmed by Ian Thompson.

items.title: Calochlaena dubia
items.content_text: New species record for Conglomerate Gully.

items.title: Brunonia australis
items.content_text: Great mass displays.

items.title: Centrolepis aristata
items.content_text: New species record for the Macedon Range.

items.title: Melicytus dentatus s.s.
items.content_text: New species record for the Macedon Range massif. One large, very old plant.

items.title: Solenogyne dominii
items.content_text: Leaf is glabrous and number of teeth fit dominii, whereas peduncle is hirsute as in gunnii.

items.title: Aphelia pumilio
items.content_text: New species record for the Macedon Range.

items.title: Montia fontana
items.content_text: ID to species by Neville Walsh. New species record for the Macedon Range. Growing in a trickle/seepage on rocks in an ephemeral part of the creek. Flowers tiny. Bifid style. Looks like a petal is missing but all flowers are like this - Levenhookia-like. Looks like 3 or 4 bilobed/notched petals.

items.title: Bulbine bulbosa
items.content_text: New species record for Conglomerate Gully.

items.title: Aphelia pumilio, Centrolepis strigosa subsp. strigosa
items.content_text: Centrolepis on the right, Aphelia on the left.

items.title: Juncus capitatus
items.content_text: New species record for Conglomerate Gully.

items.title: Histiopteris incisa
items.content_text: Reconfirmed at Conglomerate Gully. A few plants in an isolated gully downstream from waterfall.

items.title: Cicendia filiformis
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek. Common in the two main open areas at Conglomerate Gully.

items.title: Levenhookia dubia
items.content_text: New species record for the Macedon Range. Just one plant found near the base of the waterfall at Conglomerate Gully.

items.title: Tolpis barbata
items.content_text: New species record for Conglomerate Gully.

items.title: Linaria pelisseriana
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Drosera peltata s.s.
items.content_text: Main ID features distinguishing peltata s.s. from auriculata are hairy sepals (pic1) and lack of/withered basal leaves at flowering (pic2).

items.title: Wahlenbergia gracilenta s.s.
items.content_text: New species record for Conglomerate Gully. Found in open area, right of creek and above watetfall.

items.title: Solenogyne dominii
items.content_text: New species record for Conglomerate Gully. Found on track leaving open area right above waterfall and between the two entrances to the viewing platform.

items.title: Daucus glochidiatus
items.content_text: Just a few plants in the smallest creekline through the open area above the waterfall.

items.title: Centrolepis strigosa subsp. strigosa
items.content_text: New species record for the Macedon Range.

items.title: Mazus pumilio
items.content_text: Lots of plants probably a week or two from peak flowering.

Glyphipterix chrysoplanetis, Isotoma fluviatilis subsp. austr...
3 ids
items.content_text: Forrester takes advantage of the slit in the Lobelia flower as the Glyphs look on (they tend to climb down to get their feed).

items.title: Mazus pumilio
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Calandrinia calyptrata
items.content_text: A few plants surviving in rock crevices.

items.title: Hydrocotyle sibthorpioides
items.content_text: 2m mat in dried up flow area of upper reaches of creek. Frill of hairs at top of leaf stem (pic 3). Leaves glabrescent/shining above (only long fine hairs on upper surface) and some hairs visible on leaf under-surface. New species for Riddell.

items.title: Ranunculus glabrifolius
items.content_text: Fruit and leaf seem to confirm species. New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Hypericum spp.
items.content_text: Possibly H. japonicum. Large patch in dried up flow area of upper reaches of creek. Small flowers compared to gramineum plants in drier areas nearby. Would be a new species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Cassytha glabella f. dispar
items.content_text: New species record for Conglomerate Gully.

items.title: Triglochin spp.
items.content_text: What an underwater Triglochin rootall looks like when its pool has dried up.

items.title: Epacris impressa var. impressa
items.content_text: Plants are looking quite distraught after the dry weather, many are dead and those surviving have leaves just in clusters along woody stems.

items.title: Cheilanthes austrotenuifolia
items.content_text: Suffered badly this year with considerable die back but they are returning very well.

items.title: Hypoxis hygrometrica var. villosisepala
items.content_text: New species record for CGully. Pics show all ID features for this variety - sepals hairy externally, anthers bifid apically & basally, flowers often 2 per peduncle.

items.title: Pauridia glabella var. glabella
items.content_text: Lots flowering today. Flora of Victoria has it flowering Jul-Sep. 2nd pic shows the two sheathing bracteoles at base of flowering stem.

items.title: Pelargonium rodneyanum
items.content_text: Hundreds of plants but only a couple of flowers.

items.title: Tricoryne elatior
items.content_text: New species record for Conglomerate Gully. Seen lots around Riddells Creek and nearby towns in the past two weeks.

items.title: Rytidosperma pallidum
items.content_text: Seems to be flowering earlier than usual?

items.title: Triglochin striata
items.content_text: Growing among Gratiola peruviana on the edge of a pond that is slowly drying up.

items.title: Gratiola peruviana
items.content_text: In an area usually waterlogged - edge of a pool.

items.title: Leucochrysum albicans var. albicans
items.content_text: Note small moths on 2nd pic (Glyphiptera or Oecophorid moths perhaps).

items.title: Leucochrysum albicans var. albicans, Turneriprocris dolens
items.content_text: Moth is about half the size of the similar-looking Satin-green Forester, which was also about in large numbers this day (see following observation, 7803). T. dolens seen primarily on the Leucochrysum.

items.title: 3 ids
items.content_text: Nice spot with three fern species growing together out of a rock face. The large leaves are Pelargonium rodneyanum.

items.title: Cheilanthes sieberi subsp. sieberi
items.content_text: Lots of plants on a small rocky area in the forest.

items.title: Lomandra filiformis
items.content_text: Good population of the grey-leaved form of Lomandra filiformis. Leaves range from 2mm wide upwards. Right on the imaginary border of Barrm Birrm and Conglomerate Gully.

items.title: Glossodia major
items.content_text: 75 individuals in this picture.
